Fig. 7(b) shows the XRD images of SA, TOCNC, CD-TOCNC/SA, and CDs-TOCNC/SA + Pb2+, where SA has no crystal structure, and TOCNC has four peaks at 15.1°, 16.3°, 22.6° and 34°, which are located in the (101), (10
1 ¯
), (002), and (004) planes, respectively [41], indicating the crystal morphology of cellulose I. The appearance of these peaks is not evident in the CDs-TOCNC/SA map because TOCNC and SA produce cross-linked porous structures, and CDs-TOCNC/SA is encapsulated in this generated cross-linked porous structure. However, the peaks at 15.1° and 16.3° for CDs-TOCNC/SA + Pb2+ almost disappeared, and the peak at 22.6° weakened; this may be due to the destruction of some CDs-TOCNC/SA crystal structures when combined with Pb2+. However, the increase in the 34° peak may be due to the ion exchange between Pb2+ and the adsorbent, which exposes the originally wrapped crystal structure.
